      {
        "content": "Social media's current design exacerbates mental health issues by promoting addictive behaviors and unrealistic social comparisons. The dopamine-driven feedback loops of likes and shares create dependency, impacting emotional well-being and self-esteem. Continuous exposure to curated, idealized images leads to anxiety, depression, and a distorted self-image, especially among young users. Algorithms prioritize engagement over well-being, often amplifying negative content that can harm mental health. Reform is necessary to prioritize user wellness, such as implementing features that reduce addictive use and provide supportive environments for genuine connections. Without reform, social media will continue to undermine mental health globally.",
